    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-01-22T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-01-22T00:00:00-05:00" n="439"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d439">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">Hopkins: Papers</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The President’s Personal Representative</hi> (<persName
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Murphy</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Presidents Special Assistant</hi>
                        (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hopkins</hi>
                    </persName>)<note n="1" xml:id="d439fn1">The source text is handwritten.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Casablanca</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-01-22">January 22,
                            1943</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Harry</hi>—Giraud will have de Gaulle for lunch.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d439fn2">This first de Gaulle–Giraud meeting appears to be the one
                        described in de Gaulle, p. 83, and Giraud, pp. 101–103.</note>
                </p>
                <pb facs="0907" n="821" xml:id="pg_821"/>
                <p>After lunch both men will be shut in a room for private confab.</p>
                <p>After that I think the PM should receive de Gaulle<note n="3" xml:id="d439fn3"
                        >Churchill did receive de Gaulle on January 22. For accounts of the meeting,
                        see de Gaulle, pp. 86–87, and Churchill, <hi rend="italic">Hinge of
                            Fate</hi>, pp. 681–682.</note> and then the PM should lead him over to
                    the President.</p>
                <p>I think Giraud will be willing that the President be able to include in his
                    public statement something to effect that all Vichy racial laws will be
                    abolished in this area.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Bob</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
